{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UN6ozk5hXV1PU73b6M1mD6","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/*\n     2→ * step1.cu -- K_Step1 SPH density summation + strain-rate tensor + heat diffusion\n     3→ *             + exposure accumulation kernel.\n     4→ *\n     5→ * Per-particle computation:\n     6→ *   density_sum += m_j * (h^2 - |r_ij|^2)^3   for all neighbors j within h\n     7→ *   density_i = max(1.0, poly6_coeff * density_sum)\n     8→ *\n     9→ * Heat diffusion (all particles):\n    10→ *   dTdt += kappa_i * viscosity_lap_coeff * sum_j (m_j/rho_j) * (T_j - T_i) * (h - |r_ij|)\n    11→ *   where kappa_i = c_materials[mat_id].thermal_conductivity\n    12→ *\n    13→ * Exposure accumulation (all particles, via c_interactions table lookup):\n    14→ *   exposure_corrode_i += c_interactions[mat_i][mat_j].reaction_rate * W_poly6(r_sq, h_sq)\n    15→ *   exposure_heat_i += c_interactions[mat_i][mat_j].heat_exchange * max(T_j - T_i, 0) * W_poly6(r_sq, h_sq)\n    16→ *   No if/else branching on material type -- pure table lookup.\n    17→ *\n    18→ * For GRANULAR particles only, also computes the symmetric strain-rate tensor D\n    19→ * using the SPH velocity gradient with spiky gradient weighting:\n    20→ *   D_ab = 0.5 * sum_j (m_j/rho_j) * (dv_a * gradW_b + dv_b * gradW_a)\n    21→ * Then: gamma_dot = sqrt(2 * D:D) = sqrt(2 * (Dxx^2 + Dyy^2 + Dzz^2 + 2*(Dxy^2 + Dxz^2 + Dyz^2)))\n    22→ *\n    23→ * Operates on SORTED particle arrays (after hash + sort + reorder).\n    24→ * Uses 27-cell neighbor iteration with grid cell_start/cell_end tables.\n    25→ * Self-interaction IS included for density (j==i NOT skipped).\n    26→ * Self-interaction is skipped for strain-rate, heat diffusion, and exposure (j==i skipped).\n    27→ * Per-particle mass m_j supports multi-material and mass splitting.\n    28→ *\n    29→ * Ported from SPHSimLib/K_SimpleSPH_Step1.inl + K_SPH_Kernels_poly6.inl.\n    30→ * Neighbor iteration ported from SPHSimLib/K_UniformGrid_Utils.inl.\n    31→ *\n    32→ * Constant memory (c_grid, c_sim, c_precalc, c_materials, c_interactions) declared in common.cuh.\n    33→ */\n    34→\n    35→#include \"common.cuh\"\n    36→\n    37→extern \"C\" __global__\n    38→void K_Step1(\n    39→    uint            numParticles,\n    40→    const float4*   __restrict__ position,      // sorted positions\n    41→    const float4*   __restrict__ velocity,      // sorted velocities (for strain-rate)\n    42→    const float*    __restrict__ mass,           // sorted per-particle mass\n    43→    const float*    __restrict__ density_in,     // sorted density from previous step (for strain-rate m_j/rho_j weighting; NULL on first frame)\n    44→    const uint*     __restrict__ packed_info,    // sorted packed_info (for behavior class check)\n    45→    const float*    __restrict__ temperature_in, // sorted temperature (for heat diffusion)\n    46→    const uint*     __restrict__ cell_start,     // grid cell start indices\n    47→    const uint*     __restrict__ cell_end,       // grid cell end indices\n    48→    float*          __restrict__ density_out,    // output: density per particle\n    49→    float*          __restrict__ shear_rate_out, // output: gamma_dot per particle (0 for non-GRANULAR)\n    50→    float*          __restrict__ dTdt_out,       // output: temperature rate of change (heat diffusion)\n    51→    float*          __restrict__ exposure_heat_out,    // output: heat exposure from interactions\n    52→    float*          __restrict__ exposure_corrode_out  // output: corrosion exposure from interactions\n    53→) {\n    54→    uint index_i = blockIdx.x * blockDim.x + threadIdx.x;\n    55→    if (index_i >= numParticles) return;\n    56→\n    57→    // Read position of particle i\n    58→    float4 pos4_i = position[index_i];\n    59→    float3 pos_i = make_float3(pos4_i.x, pos4_i.y, pos4_i.z);\n    60→\n    61→    float h    = c_sim.smoothing_length;\n    62→    float h_sq = c_sim.smoothing_length_sq;\n    63→\n    64→    // Check if this particle is GRANULAR\n    65→    uint pi_i = __ldg(&packed_info[index_i]);\n    66→    int behavior_i = GET_BEHAVIOR(pi_i);\n    67→    uint mat_id_i = GET_MATERIAL_ID(pi_i);\n    68→    bool is_granular = (behavior_i == GRANULAR);\n    69→\n    70→    // Read velocity for strain-rate (only used if GRANULAR, but cheap to read)\n    71→    float3 vel_i;\n    72→    if (is_granular) {\n    73→        float4 vel4_i = velocity[index_i];\n    74→        vel_i = make_float3(vel4_i.x, vel4_i.y, vel4_i.z);\n    75→    }\n    76→\n    77→    // Read temperature for heat diffusion\n    78→    float T_i = __ldg(&temperature_in[index_i]);\n    79→    float kappa_i = c_materials[mat_id_i].thermal_conductivity;\n    80→\n    81→    // Density accumulator (variable part of Poly6 kernel)\n    82→    float sum_density = 0.0f;\n    83→\n    84→    // Heat diffusion accumulator: dTdt\n    85→    float sum_dTdt = 0.0f;\n    86→\n    87→    // Exposure accumulators (from c_interactions table lookup)\n    88→    float sum_exposure_heat = 0.0f;\n    89→    float sum_exposure_corrode = 0.0f;\n    90→\n    91→    // Strain-rate tensor accumulators (6 symmetric components)\n    92→    // D_xx, D_yy, D_zz, D_xy, D_xz, D_yz\n    93→    float Dxx = 0.0f, Dyy = 0.0f, Dzz = 0.0f;\n    94→    float Dxy = 0.0f, Dxz = 0.0f, Dyz = 0.0f;\n    95→\n    96→    // Grid cell of particle i\n    97→    int3 cell_i = make_int3(\n    98→        (int)((pos_i.x - c_grid.grid_min.x) * c_grid.grid_delta.x),\n    99→        (int)((pos_i.y - c_grid.grid_min.y) * c_grid.grid_delta.y),\n   100→        (int)((pos_i.z - c_grid.grid_min.z) * c_grid.grid_delta.z)\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_016myLLq9AYQ6ECjeFvfw5cw","session_id":"d557a6a8-dde9-41cf-ab3a-fa6ac2ce30b6","uuid":"1868cbc9-b6b0-452f-9d49-8c070bbd0e52"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SnRQEbRohhEeNCddrygrry","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/*\n     2→ * step2.cu -- K_Step2 pressure, viscosity, and XSPH force kernel.\n     3→ *\n     4→ * Per-particle computation:\n     5→ *   1. Tait EOS pressure from density and per-material EOS parameters\n     6→ *   2. For GRANULAR: first pass to compute gamma_dot (strain rate) for mu(I)\n     7→ *   3. Neighbor loop: accumulate pressure force (spiky gradient),\n     8→ *      viscosity force (viscosity Laplacian), and XSPH correction (FLUID only)\n     9→ *   4. Write sph_force (float4) and veleval (float4, XSPH-corrected)\n    10→ *\n    11→ * mu(I) rheology (GRANULAR only):\n    12→ *   - gamma_dot computed from SPH velocity gradient in first neighbor pass\n    13→ *   - I = gamma_dot * spacing / sqrt(p_eff / rho_i)\n    14→ *   - mu_I = mu_s + (mu_2 - mu_s) / (1 + I0 / max(I, 1e-8))\n    15→ *   - eta_i = min(mu_max, mu0 + mu_I * p_eff / (gamma_dot + 1e-6))\n    16→ *   - Harmonic mean eta_ij for GRANULAR-GRANULAR pairs\n    17→ *\n    18→ * Skips STATIC (behavior_class == 3) and SLEEPING particles (early return).\n    19→ *\n    20→ * Constant memory used:\n    21→ *   c_grid, c_sim, c_precalc -- from common.cuh (shared with other kernels)\n    22→ *   c_materials              -- from common.cuh (per-material EOS properties)\n    23→ *   c_granular               -- local to this module (mu(I) parameters)\n    24→ *\n    25→ * Ported from SPHSimLib/K_SimpleSPH_Step2.inl with Tait EOS and multi-material\n    26→ * behavior classes per acceptance criteria.\n    27→ */\n    28→\n    29→#include \"common.cuh\"\n    30→\n    31→#ifndef M_PI\n    32→#define M_PI 3.14159265358979323846f\n    33→#endif\n    34→\n    35→/* ======================================================================\n    36→ * GranularParams -- mu(I) rheology parameters.\n    37→ * Local to this module; uploaded from Python before kernel launch.\n    38→ * ====================================================================== */\n    39→\n    40→struct GranularParams {\n    41→    float mu_s;               // static friction coefficient (0.36)\n    42→    float mu_2;               // dynamic friction coefficient (0.70)\n    43→    float I0;                 // inertial number reference (0.3)\n    44→    float mu_max;             // viscosity clamp (10000 Pa*s)\n    45→    float particle_spacing;   // particle spacing d (0.02)\n    46→    float mu0;                // base viscosity for GRANULAR\n    47→    float xsph_epsilon;       // XSPH blending factor (0.5)\n    48→    float _pad0;              // padding to 32 bytes\n    49→};\n    50→\n    51→__constant__ GranularParams c_granular;\n    52→\n    53→/* ======================================================================\n    54→ * Tait EOS pressure computation\n    55→ *\n    56→ * Reads per-material rest_density, eos_stiffness, eos_gamma from c_materials.\n    57→ *\n    58→ *   FLUID:    p_raw = k * (pow(rho/rho0, 7) - 1);  p = max(p_raw, -0.5*k)\n    59→ *   GRANULAR: p_raw = k * (pow(rho/rho0, 7) - 1);  p = max(p_raw, 0)\n    60→ *   GAS:      p = k_gas * max(rho - rho0, 0)        (gamma=1, linear)\n    61→ * ====================================================================== */\n    62→\n    63→__device__ inline float compute_pressure(float rho_i, int behavior, uint mat_id) {\n    64→    float rho0 = c_materials[mat_id].rest_density;\n    65→    float k    = c_materials[mat_id].eos_stiffness;\n    66→\n    67→    if (behavior == GAS) {\n    68→        // GAS: linear EOS with gamma=1\n    69→        return k * fmaxf(rho_i - rho0, 0.0f);\n    70→    }\n    71→\n    72→    // FLUID / GRANULAR: Tait EOS with gamma=7\n    73→    float ratio = rho_i / fmaxf(rho0, 1e-6f);\n    74→    float p_raw = k * (powf(ratio, 7.0f) - 1.0f);\n    75→\n    76→    if (behavior == GRANULAR) {\n    77→        return fmaxf(p_raw, 0.0f);\n    78→    }\n    79→    // FLUID: allow small tensile pressure\n    80→    return fmaxf(p_raw, -0.5f * k);\n    81→}\n    82→\n    83→/* ======================================================================\n    84→ * SPH kernel variable parts\n    85→ * (constant coefficients applied in PostCalc via c_precalc)\n    86→ * ====================================================================== */\n    87→\n    88→/**\n    89→ * Spiky gradient variable part: (r/|r|) * (h - |r|)^2\n    90→ * Points AWAY from neighbor (r = pos_i - pos_j).\n    91→ * No coefficient -- that's in pressure_precalc.\n    92→ */\n    93→__device__ inline float3 grad_spiky_variable(float3 r, float rlen, float h) {\n    94→    float h_rlen = h - rlen;\n    95→    float inv_rlen = 1.0f / rlen;\n    96→    return make_float3(\n    97→        r.x * inv_rlen * (h_rlen * h_rlen),\n    98→        r.y * inv_rlen * (h_rlen * h_rlen),\n    99→        r.z * inv_rlen * (h_rlen * h_rlen)\n   100→    );\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_016myLLq9AYQ6ECjeFvfw5cw","session_id":"d557a6a8-dde9-41cf-ab3a-fa6ac2ce30b6","uuid":"03922fb5-90c1-4da7-9bf3-f9648a162594"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016myLLq9AYQ6ECjeFvfw5cw","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Excellent! Now I have a comprehensive understanding. Let me create a final summary document:\n\n## Codebase Structure Summary: GPUSPHSim (Falling Sand 3D)\n\n### 1. MAIN PYTHON SIMULATION FILES (Orchestration & Pipeline)\n\n**Primary Orchestrator:**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/simulation.py` (lines 1-486)\n  - Main `Simulation` class that orchestrates full SPH pipeline\n  - Allocates freelist for dead particles (line 103-105)\n  - Resets freelist each step (line 310)\n  - Calls Reactions → Spawn pipeline (lines 312-345)\n  - Particle count passed as `n = world._high_water` (lines 412, 430)\n\n**World State Management:**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/world.py` (lines 1-304)\n  - `World` class manages all SoA arrays on GPU\n  - Allocates both unsorted and sorted (temporary) arrays\n  - Uses `_high_water` to track max particle index (line 49)\n  - Tracks `num_active` via `count_nonzero(packed_info)` (lines 107-112)\n  - Dead particles marked as `packed_info=0` (material_id=0, STATIC behavior)\n  - All arrays pre-allocated once (lines 52-100)\n\n### 2. DEAD PARTICLE MANAGEMENT (Freelist System)\n\n**Freelist Allocation & Management:**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/spawn.py` (lines 98-115)\n  - `allocate_freelist(max_particles)` returns `(dead_indices, dead_count)` (lines 103-115)\n  - `dead_indices`: uint32 array of dead particle indices (stack)\n  - `dead_count`: uint32 atomic counter (1 element)\n  - `reset_freelist(dead_count)` zeros counter each step (lines 118-120)\n  - `SPAWN_N = 3` particles spawned per water boil (line 100)\n\n**Freelist Population (Reactions):**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/reactions.py` (lines 106-177)\n  - Kernel populates freelist when particles die from:\n    - Corrosion (health ≤ 0): lines 191-205 in spawn.cu\n    - Gas lifetime expiry: lines 207-223 in spawn.cu\n  - Uses `atomicAdd(dead_count)` to push dead particle indices\n  - Backward compatible: accepts optional `dead_indices`/`dead_count` pointers\n\n**Freelist Consumption (Spawn):**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/spawn.py` (lines 130-202)\n  - `compute_spawn()` kernel consumes freelist for spawning steam\n  - Uses `atomicSub(dead_count, N)` to claim N slots for spawned particles\n  - Restores count if insufficient slots available (graceful failure)\n  - Source water particle marked DEAD, NOT added back to freelist (race avoidance)\n\n### 3. PHYSICS KERNEL LAUNCH STRUCTURE\n\n**Step1 (Density + Strain Rate + Heat + Exposure):**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/step1.py` (lines 248-346)\n  - `compute_step1()` kernel launch (lines 248-262)\n  - Receives particle count implicitly from array shapes\n  - Grid calculation: `((n + BLOCK_SIZE-1) // BLOCK_SIZE,)` (line 322)\n  - Outputs density, shear_rate, dTdt, exposure_heat, exposure_corrode\n\n**Step2 (Pressure + Viscosity + XSPH):**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/step2.py` (lines 200+)\n  - Similar grid launch pattern\n  - Reads sorted arrays, outputs sph_force and veleval\n  - Block size: 128-256 typical\n\n**Integrate (Symplectic Euler + Boundaries):**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/integrate.py` (lines 102-200)\n  - Kernel processes sorted arrays\n  - Writes back to unsorted arrays via `sort_indexes` permutation\n  - Updates position, velocity, color, packed_info, sleep_counter, temperature\n\n### 4. SoA ARRAY LAYOUTS (Data Structure)\n\n**Unsorted Arrays (main particle storage):**\n- Float4: `position, velocity, veleval, sph_force, color`\n- Float: `density, mass, temperature, health, lifetime, shear_rate, exposure_heat, exposure_corrode`\n- Uint32: `packed_info`\n- Uint8: `sleep_counter`\n\n**Sorted Temporary Buffers (pre-allocated in World):**\n- Exact same layout as unsorted, reused every frame\n- Written by fused_reorder kernel\n- Read by Step1, Step2, Reactions, Spawn kernels\n- Written back to unsorted by Integrate\n\n**Key Array Types:**\n- `packed_info` bitfield (uint32): bits [7:0]=material_id, [9:8]=behavior_class, [10]=is_sleeping, [11]=spawn_flag, [12]=just_woke\n\n### 5. CUDA KERNEL FILES & PARTICLE COUNT HANDLING\n\n**Common Header:**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/physics/kernels/common.cuh` (lines 1-172)\n  - Defines all struct layouts (MaterialProps, Interaction, GridParams, SimParams, PrecalcParams)\n  - Defines packed_info macros\n  - Constant memory declarations (c_grid, c_sim, c_precalc, c_materials, c_interactions)\n\n**Kernel Files (all receive `numParticles` as first parameter):**\n1. `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/physics/kernels/hash_sort.cu` (2006 bytes)\n   - `K_CalcHash(uint numParticles, ...)`\n   \n2. `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/physics/kernels/build_grid.cu` (1327 bytes)\n   - `K_BuildDataStruct(uint numParticles, ...)`\n   - Clears cell tables, detects cell boundaries\n\n3. `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/physics/kernels/fused_reorder.cu` (2609 bytes)\n   - `K_FusedReorder(uint numParticles, ...)`\n   - Gathers all SoA arrays via permutation\n\n4. `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/physics/kernels/step1.cu` (11932 bytes, lines 37-55)\n   - `K_Step1(uint numParticles, ...)`\n   - Per-thread: `if (index_i >= numParticles) return;`\n\n5. `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/physics/kernels/step2.cu` (17683 bytes, lines 63+)\n   - `K_Step2(uint numParticles, ...)`\n   - Tait EOS pressure, mu(I) rheology for GRANULAR\n   - Skips STATIC and SLEEPING particles\n\n6. `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/physics/kernels/integrate.cu` (16875 bytes)\n   - `K_Integrate(uint numParticles, ...)`\n   - Symplectic Euler integration with SDF boundary collisions\n   - Writes back to unsorted arrays\n\n7. `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/physics/kernels/reactions.cu` (8094 bytes, lines 79-224)\n   - `K_Reactions(uint numParticles, uint frame, ...)`\n   - Phase transitions (ICE→WATER, LAVA→STONE, WATER→SPAWN_FLAG, STEAM→WATER)\n   - Combustion (WOOD/OIL/GUNPOWDER → FIRE + explosion)\n   - Corrosion health decay and gas lifetime decay\n   - Populates freelist on death (lines 191-223)\n\n8. `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/physics/kernels/spawn.cu` (6074 bytes, lines 56-171)\n   - `K_SpawnGas(uint numParticles, ...)`\n   - Processes HAS_SPAWN_FLAG particles\n   - Claims N freelist slots via atomicSub (lines 86-109)\n   - Writes spawned particles to freelist slots (lines 128-163)\n   - Marks source as DEAD (line 168)\n\n9. `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/physics/kernels/wake.cu` (4940 bytes)\n   - Wake propagation for sleeping particles\n\n### 6. COMPILATION & CONSTANT MEMORY\n\n**Module Pattern (all physics files):**\n- Each module has `_get_module()` that compiles `.cu` via CuPy RawModule\n- Caches compiled module globally\n- Ensures PTX compilation for high GPU architectures (lines 33-46 pattern)\n\n**Constant Memory Uploads:**\n- `upload_grid_params()` → `c_grid` (GridParams)\n- `upload_sim_params()` → `c_sim` (SimParams, includes dt)\n- `upload_precalc_params()` → `c_precalc` (PrecalcParams)\n- `upload_materials()` → `c_materials[32]` (MaterialProps array)\n- `upload_interactions()` → `c_interactions[32][32]` (Interaction matrix)\n- `upload_granular_params()` → `c_granular` (GranularParams, step2 only)\n\nAll uploads via `cupy.cuda.runtime.memcpy()` to module's global pointers\n\n### 7. TEST INFRASTRUCTURE\n\n**Test Files:**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/test_reactions.py` (559 lines)\n  - 22 tests for reactions kernel\n  - Tests phase transitions, combustion, corrosion, gas lifetime\n  - Tests freelist integration (lines 592-666)\n  - 500K stress test (lines 451-511)\n\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/test_spawn.py` (920 lines)\n  - 16 tests for spawn kernel and freelist system\n  - Tests mass conservation, scattered freelist indices (lines 376-431)\n  - Tests freelist exhaustion and partial exhaustion\n  - Tests reactions↔spawn end-to-end (lines 702-789)\n  - 500K stress test with 10K spawning water particles (lines 792-878)\n\n**Test Patterns:**\n- Setup phase with `setup_params()` to upload constants\n- Create particle arrays via `make_particles()` or `make_sorted_arrays()`\n- Launch kernel\n- Verify results by downloading and checking\n- All tests use packed_info bitfield macros (MAKE_PACKED, GET_MATERIAL_ID, etc.)\n\n### 8. SIMULATION STEP EXECUTION FLOW\n\n**Per-frame simulation substep (`_sim_step`, simulation.py lines 259-396):**\n1. Hash particle positions (line 264)\n2. Sort by hash (lines 267-271)\n3. Fused reorder all arrays (lines 274-284)\n4. Build grid cell_start/cell_end (lines 287-289)\n5. Step1: density + strain + heat + exposure (lines 292-306)\n6. Reset freelist counter (line 310)\n7. Reactions: phase transitions + freelist population (lines 316-327)\n8. Spawn: consume freelist to spawn steam (lines 330-345)\n9. Step2: pressure + viscosity + XSPH (lines 348-358)\n10. Integrate: write back to unsorted (lines 363-383)\n11. Wake propagation (lines 387-393)\n\n**Particle Count Flow:**\n- `n = world._high_water` (line 412)\n- All sorted slices: `[:n]` to operate on active particles\n- Grid size: `((n + BLOCK_SIZE-1) // BLOCK_SIZE,)` for each kernel\n- Dead particles (packed_info==0) processed in-place but skipped via early return\n\n### 9. KEY FILES BY PURPOSE\n\n**Main Simulation:**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/simulation.py` - Pipeline orchestrator\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/world.py` - SoA memory manager\n\n**Physics Modules (Python wrappers):**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/hash_sort.py` - Spatial hashing\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/build_grid.py` - Grid structure\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/fused_reorder.py` - Array reordering\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/step1.py` - Density computation\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/step2.py` - Force computation\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/integrate.py` - Integration\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/reactions.py` - Phase transitions + freelist\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/spawn.py` - Particle spawning\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/wake.py` - Wake propagation\n\n**Materials & Interactions:**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/materials.py` - Material definitions\n\n**CUDA Kernels:**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/physics/kernels/common.cuh` - Shared definitions\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/physics/kernels/*.cu` - Individual kernels\n\n**Tests:**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/test_*.py` - Unit/integration tests (15 test files)"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a2b46bf (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 147526\ntool_uses: 24\nduration_ms: 65132</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d557a6a8-dde9-41cf-ab3a-fa6ac2ce30b6","uuid":"ab3d8599-2001-4031-9c56-4826af8a411f","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Explore the gpusphsim codebase structure. I need to understand:\n1. The main Python simulation files (especially anything related to particles, SoA arrays, simulation stepping)\n2. Where dead particles are managed (dead_indices, dead_count, particle status/type arrays)\n3. Where physics kernels are launched (what arrays they operate on, how particle count is passed)\n4. Any existing compaction or particle management utilities\n5. The CUDA kernel files (.cu) and how they reference particle counts\n6. The test infrastructure and existing tests\n\nFocus on the Python files in the fallingsand3d/ directory and any CUDA kernel files. Give me file paths and key line numbers for all relevant code.","agentId":"a2b46bf","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Excellent! Now I have a comprehensive understanding. Let me create a final summary document:\n\n## Codebase Structure Summary: GPUSPHSim (Falling Sand 3D)\n\n### 1. MAIN PYTHON SIMULATION FILES (Orchestration & Pipeline)\n\n**Primary Orchestrator:**\n- `/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/simulation.py` (lines 1-486)\n  - Main `Simulation` class that orchestrates full SP